To make an interface internal so that it does not appear in the public interface of the generated Python SDK, you should use the `@access(Access.internal, "python")` decorator from the Azure.ClientGenerator.Core library on the interface itself. However, simply marking the interface or its operations as internal is not sufficient if any public operation references the interface or its models, as access is propagated from usage.

The correct approach is:
- Apply `@access(Access.internal, "python")` to the interface you want to hide.
- Ensure that none of its operations or models are referenced by any public operations or models. If any public operation references them, those types will be promoted to public regardless of the decorator.

Example:
```typespec
import "@azure-tools/typespec-client-generator-core";
using Azure.ClientGenerator.Core;

@access(Access.internal, "python")
interface EvaluationResultsOperations {
  @access(Access.internal, "python")
  op getEvaluationResults(): EvaluationResult;
}

@access(Access.internal, "python")
model EvaluationResult {
  value: string;
}
```

If you do this and ensure that `EvaluationResultsOperations` and its models are not referenced by any public operations, they will not appear in the public Python SDK client.

If you still see the interface in the public client, double-check that no public operation or model references it, directly or indirectly. Access is propagated, so any public usage will override the internal marking.

There is no supported way to generate the interface but keep it hidden from the public client if it is referenced by public operations/models. The suppression or patching approach is not recommended and not supported by TypeSpec best practices.
